1. multi-inputs for the neural network
2. Write a custom Triton or CUDA kernel that groups similar operators together to minimize warp divergence.
    -In an ONN, if Thread A is calculating $sin(x)$ and Thread B is calculating $exp(x)$, the GPU hits Divergence. It can’t do both at once, so it serializes them—effectively pausing Thread B while A finishes, then pausing A while B finishes.
    -This is why your scaling is horrible: As you add more nodes (and thus more variety in operators), the probability of warp divergence skyrockets.
3. Group all "Sine" nodes and calculate them in one big block, then group all "Exponential" nodes. Don't interleave them in the same layer.
4. Lookup Tables (LUTs): For symbolic regression, you often don't need 64-bit precision. Pre-calculate your $sin$ and $exp$ values into a 1D texture map (Lookup Table). Fetching a value from memory is often faster than calculating a 10th-order polynomial expansion.
5. Memory Coalescing: Ensure adjacent threads access adjacent memory locations. Rearrange tensor layouts so node data is contiguous in memory.
6. Shared Memory Caching: Cache frequently used intermediate values (like routing weights, node outputs) in shared memory to reduce global memory bandwidth.
7. FP16/TensorCore: Use mixed precision (PyTorch AMP) where possible. TensorCores can dramatically speed up matrix operations if precision loss is acceptable.
8. Kernel Fusion: Fuse multiple small ops into one kernel launch to reduce kernel launch overhead and intermediate memory writes.